syntax is wrong across multiple files. In Maestro, the `optional` property needs
to be nested inside the command map, not as a sibling when the command is in sca
lar form.\n\nFor example:\n```yaml\n- assertVisible: "完善资料"\n  optional: tru
e\n```\n\nThis is invalid YAML/Maestro syntax. It should be:\n```yaml\n- assertV
isible:\n    text: "完善资料"\n    optional: true\n```\n\nSimilarly:\n```yaml\n-
swipe:\n    direction: LEFT\n    optional: true\n```\nThis one is actually corre
ct because `swipe` is already in map form.\n\nBut:\n```yaml\n- tapOn:\n    id: "
pass_button"\n    optional: true\n```\nThis is correct because `tapOn` is in map
form.\n\nThe problematic ones are:\n1. `flows/auth/login.yaml`:\n```yaml\n- asse
rtVisible: "完善资料"\n  optional: true\n```\nShould be:\n```yaml\n- assertVisib
le:\n    text: "完善资料"\n    optional: true\n```\n\nAnd:\n```yaml\n- assertVis
ible:\n    id: "tab_home"\n    optional: true\n```\nThis one should actually be 
correct... wait, let me re-read the error. The error says line 22. Let me check 
the exact content of the file again.\n\nActually, looking at the file:\n```yaml\
n- assertVisible: "完善资料"\n  optional: true\n- assertVisible:\n    id: "tab_h
ome"\n    optional: true\n```\n\nLine 21 is `- assertVisible: "完善资料"` and li
ne 22 is `  optional: true`. The issue is that when `assertVisible` takes a scal
ar value, you can\'t add `optional` as a sibling in the same list item because o
f YAML parsing. The parser sees `assertVisible` with value "完善资料" and then d
oesn\'t know what to do with `optional`.\n\nActually, in YAML:\n```yaml\n- asser
tVisible: "完善资料"\n  optional: true\n```\n\nThis IS valid YAML - it creates a
single object with keys `assertVisible` and `optional`. But Maestro\'s parser fo
r `assertVisible` might not expect `optional` as a top-level key when the comman
d is specified this way. The Maestro parser probably sees the command type as `a
ssertVisible` and expects only assertion-related fields, not `optional`.\n\nActu
ally wait, the error says "Unrecognized field \'optional\' (class maestro.orches
tra.yaml.YamlFluentCommand)". This means the command is being parsed as YamlFlue
ntCommand, which is a generic command class, and it doesn\'t recognize `optional
